{ "answer": ["Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever","RMSF"], "clues": ["Originally dubbed 'black measles' due to its distinct, dark purplish rash, this was first identified in the 1890s in Idaho","In 1922, the Governor of Montana lost both his daughter and his son-in-law to the disease. This motivated a massive influx of funding and research and Dr. Spencer of the US Public Health Service led a research team where he injected a large dose of mashed wood ticks which actually worked as a vaccine","This disease is endemic to the Americas with cases concentrated in the US, Mexico, and Central and South America. Despite its name, this arthropod borne disease actually has the highest incidence in the Southeast and South-Central regions of the United States"] }
